		{"id":"71fd6b9e287608d5","type":"text","text":"## 16/9 ->  4^2 / 3^2 \n\n## (4x4) /(3x3)\n\n## (2x2x2x2)/(3x3)\n\n## 4 Explicate Doublings (even, tori), 2 implicate Triplings (odd, klein)","x":-5105,"y":2642,"width":250,"height":303},
		{"id":"794a34bf73f4e870","type":"text","text":"The elementary building blocks of the Klein bottle may be slightly modified to produce several different geometric versions of the Klein bottles. Here we see a Klein bottle with a triple symmetry.\n\nEvery non-orientable tube is a Klein bottle. Here the tube has three inversions such that it is non-orientable. In fact, we can use increase the degree of symmetry to any odd number and always produce a topological Klein bottle. Even numbers yield an orientable torus.","x":-5708,"y":2642,"width":250,"height":231},
		{"id":"4a06774e2dc7dac5","type":"text","text":"Based on the provided sources, the essence of recursive language model (RLM) techniques and looping can be understood as a shift from \"stuffing context\" into a model to \"agentic reasoning over time.\" When framed via the **Thread-Based Engineering** taxonomy (Base, P, C, F, B, L, Z threads), these techniques represent the evolution from simple prompts to high-autonomy workflows.\n\nHere is the essence of these techniques framed via agent threads.\n\n1. The L-Thread (Long Thread): The Container for Looping\n\nThe **L-Thread** serves as the architectural foundation for looping. It is defined as a high-autonomy, long-duration workflow where an agent executes hundreds or thousands of tool calls without human intervention.\n\n• **The \"Ralph Wiggum\" Loop:** This technique is effectively an implementation of an L-Thread. It is an \"AI coding loop that stubbornly keeps iterating on its topic... until it finally succeeds\". In practice, this often involves a \"while loop\" over an agent, allowing it to re-attempt tasks repeatedly.\n\n• **The Mechanism:** The key to making these L-Threads work is the **Stop Hook**. This allows deterministic code (traditional programming) to intercept an agent's attempt to finish, run validation commands, and force the agent back into the loop if the work is incorrect.\n\n• **Context Management (The \"True\" Ralph):** A critical distinction exists in how this loop handles context.\n\n    ◦ _The Plugin Approach:_ Simply prevents the agent from exiting, which leads to \"context rot\" (diminishing intelligence as the context window fills).\n\n    ◦ _The \"True\" Framework:_ To maintain the \"smart area\" of the context window (0–100k tokens), a proper loop should start a **brand new session** for every iteration. This refreshes the context window while passing forward a \"progress.md\" file to retain learnings,.\n\n2. The B-Thread (Big Thread): RLM as Meta-Structure\n\nThe **Recursive Language Model (RLM)** technique is best framed as a sophisticated **B-Thread** (Big Thread). A B-Thread is a meta-structure where a primary agent prompts sub-agents or processes to perform specific work.\n\n• **The RLM Approach:** Instead of feeding a massive document (like a legal contract or codebase) into the context window, the RLM uses a **REPL (Read-Evaluate-Print Loop)**. The model treats the data as a variable in a Python script rather than text in its context.\n\n• **Recursive Decomposition:** The primary agent \"virtualizes\" the memory. It performs Python operations (slicing, regex) to find relevant chunks and then recursively hands those chunks off to a sub-agent (or a fresh instance of itself) to analyze,.\n\n• **Dependency Graphs:** This technique shifts the mental model of complex data from a \"story book\" (read end-to-end) to a **dependency graph** (nodes and edges of logic). This allows the agent to perform \"multihop reasoning\" without suffering from context rot.\n\n3. The C-Thread (Chained Thread): Verification & Phases\n\nBoth looping and RLMs rely heavily on the **C-Thread** (Chained Thread) logic, where work is broken into distinct phases (Plan, Build, Review) to ensure reliability.\n\n• **Specialized Self-Validation:** To make a loop safe, the agent must validate its own work. This is achieved through **Specialized Hooks**. For example, a \"CSV Edit\" agent might trigger a post-tool hook that runs a Python script to validate the CSV format immediately after editing. If it fails, the agent is instructed to fix it,.\n\n• **Inline Verification:** In advanced setups (like high-stakes writing), verification is embedded _within_ the generation process. As the agent generates a claim, it pauses to verify that specific claim via a sub-agent (a specialized C-Thread) before continuing generation. This prevents a \"chain of confident nonsense\" rooted in an early hallucination,.\n\n4. The Goal: The Z-Thread (Zero Touch)\n\nThe ultimate objective of combining Recursive Language Models with looping structures is to achieve the **Z-Thread**.\n\n• **Definition:** This is a \"Zero Touch\" thread where the human reviews nothing. The trust in the system is so high that the review node is removed entirely,.\n\n• **How to achieve it:** You achieve Z-Threads not by \"vibe coding,\" but by increasing the density of deterministic checks (code execution) and recursive logic (agents validating agents). As the \"thickness\" of the thread increases (via recursion and parallel sub-agents), the necessity for human intervention decreases,.\n\nSummary of the Essence\n\n• **Recursion (RLM)** is the solution to **Context Rot** and **Complexity**. It replaces \"reading\" with \"executing\" and \"searching\" via code,.\n\n• **Looping (Ralph)** is the solution to **Persistence**. It forces the agent to retry until a deterministic condition is met.\n\n• **Agent Threads** are the **Unit of Measurement**. You improve by running _more_ threads (P-Thread), _longer_ loops (L-Thread), and _thicker_ recursive structures (B-Thread).","x":-12000,"y":3833,"width":1823,"height":1039},
		{"id":"78371ddfd48d4c04","type":"text","text":"## Divide by 4 = 4x(25%)\n\n## 36/4 = 9 --- 64/4 = 16 ->>>\n\n## 16/9\n\n## 64x36 = 2304 = 48^2 =    (64-18)x(36+12) = ((2x2x2x2x2x2)-(2x3x3))x((3x3x2x2)+(3x2x2))","x":-1106,"y":2772,"width":494,"height":285},
